1. Why are push and pop O(1) in a stack?
   Because stacks only interact with the 'top' element. In an array/list, adding or 
   removing from the end doesn't require shifting other elements. In a linked list, 
   we only update the head pointer, which takes constant time.

2. What makes a stack different from a queue?
   The order of processing. A stack is LIFO (Last-In, First-Out), meaning the newest 
   item is removed first. A queue is FIFO (First-In, First-Out), meaning the oldest 
